RCH0011[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Written evidence submitted[bold] by Jonathan Stanley for the Independent Children’s Homes Association (ICHA). [bold]The ICHA is the largest independent children’s homes membership organisation. 
[normal] 
[normal]It provides evidence-based and informed policy and practice leadership for the sector. 
[normal] 
[normal]We wish to ensure the 
[normal]C
[normal]ommittee has the evidence and experience that supports the consistent views of providers. 
[normal]Much of what is being taken 
[normal]in the debate 
[normal]as conventional wisdom
[normal] 
[normal]has not been given rigorous scrutiny. 
[normal] 
[normal]Sensationalist media interpretation and reporting needs to be set aside in favour of robust analysis of the evidence and to uphold the cardinal principle held by all stakeholders: ‘the right placement at the right time for the right child at the right cost.’
[normal]I would be happy to give evidence in person to the Committee.
[normal]The person making this submission[bold]Jonathan Stanley, the Chief Executive Officer of the ICHA, has 40 years of working in residential child care across local authority, voluntary and independent sectors, managing residential and associated integrated provision (education, care, health) for national resources that address the learning, emotional, and social needs of young people. He is Principal Partner of the National Centre for Excellence in Residential Child Care. 
[normal] 
[normal]He was a member of the work groups for the DfE regarding the reform of residential child care. 
[normal]Summary[bold]Even with the pref[bold]erence for family and community-[bold]based placements[bold],[bold] the numbers of children requiring a children’s home remains consistent year on year [bold](page 6 DfE data pack September 2013)
